{% block article_content %}
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    Understanding permissions
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    Most uses of Find Case Law judgments are free under the
    {% call link(href=url("open_justice_licence")) %}
      Open Justice Licence
    {%- endcall -%}
    . This includes commercial use such as incorporating judgments into products or applications.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, if you want to perform computational analysis, you need to apply for a separate licence. Computational analysis includes any programmatic searching in bulk across Find Case Law records to identify, extract or enrich contents within the records.
  </p>
  <p>Here's what you can do freely, when you need permission and how to apply.</p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    What you can do freely
  {% endcall %}
  <p>You don't need permission for most uses of Find Case Law judgments, including:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      reading and downloading judgments
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      using them for legal research and case preparation
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      quoting them in academic work, articles, or publications
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      sharing links to judgments
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      teaching and educational purposes
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      personal reference and study
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      commercial use, such as incorporating into products or applications
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    When you need permission
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    You need to apply for a licence if you want to perform computational analysis. You can read a more detailed description of computational analysis in our glossary.
  </p>
  <p>
    When you need permission explains what counts as computational analysis and whether your intended use requires a licence.
  </p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    How to apply for a licence
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    If you need to perform computational analysis, we have a straightforward application process. You can read a more detailed description of computational analysis in our
    {% call link(href=url("glossary")) %}
      glossary
    {%- endcall -%}
    .
  </p>
  <p>What you need to apply for a licence explains:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      the 6 sections of the application form
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      the 29 questions you'll need to answer
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      how to prepare your application
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  <p>Licence application process explains:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      how applications are assessed
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      the approval process
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      timelines and what to expect
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  <p>There are no costs to apply for a licence to perform computational analysis.</p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    Legal framework
  {% endcall %}
  <p>If you need the detailed legal terms, read our legal framework for:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      the Open Justice Licence terms
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      technical specifications for licensed uses
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      legal definitions and conditions
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  {% call card(title="Questions about permissions", title_tag="h2") %}
    <p>
      If you're unsure whether you need a licence, visit
      {% call link(href=url("when_you_need_permission")) %}
        When you need permission
      {%- endcall -%}
      {{ " " }}for guidance, or contact us at
      {% call link(href="mailto:caselawlicence@nationalarchives.gov.uk") %}
        caselawlicence@nationalarchives.gov.uk
      {% endcall %}
    </p>
    <p>
      Most people using Find Case Law for research, legal work, journalism or commercial products don't need a licence â€“ you can start using judgments freely right away under the Open Justice Licence.
    </p>
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock article_content %}
